Wow. I don't even know where to start! I have been here a dozen times at least and I never have had a bad experience. The food is perfection. When I was pregnant with my daughter, I would Uber here on lunch just to get the crawfish beignets. Brunch is a long wait on the weekends but 100% worth it.

Finally got around to eating at Brenda's, I just can't believe it took me so long to do so. I came on a weekday and avoided the terrifying long waits I hear about. I wrote my name on the chalkboard and was seated within 10 minutes. Upon sitting down, I knew that I wanted to order the watermelon iced tea. It was really refreshing and perfect for a hot day. My sister and I ordered the Shrimp and grits, catfish po boy and crawfish beignets. Everything was delicious, service was efficient and attentive. I really liked the atmosphere as well, the entire place was very bright and lively. Overall, really enjoyed the soul food. This will definitely not be my last visit!

So worth the wait! Every dishes that we had ordered were perfectly seasoned and delicious. Shrimp & grits is a must along with the crawfish beignet!

Food was excellent!!!! Visiting San Fran with classmates for a medical conference and came here for our last day. We all ordered off of the specials menu and we were all very pleased. As southerners we were all very impressed with the southern style breakfast we highly recommend!

I've been here only once or twice, a few years ago, mostly due to the hassle of getting a spot here for brunch. Beignets were wonderful though, as with everything else. Decor back then had nice antique mirrors, wonder if they have those still? Will visit soon again.

One of the better brunches I've experienced in recent memory. I was told to come early, so my friends and I arrived at 9:30am, and there was already a pretty long line. However, since we were a party of 3, we were seated after only about 20 minutes. We had to get rid of our Philz coffee, because they don't allow outside coffee, which I felt was a little ridiculous. However, they did allow Libby Jane coffee, since it's a sister establishment of Brenda's. Anyways, we sat and got more coffee, ordered the beignet flight and our entrees. I predictably went with the crispy pork belly special, which came with cheesy grits, onion relish, and a poached egg. The pork belly slab was pretty sizable, and the grits were super rich, albeit a bit on the soupier side. But the dish came together very well, and I'm glad I ordered it. The sweet beignets were all delicious (plain, chocolate, and apple), and even the crawfish beignet was pretty good, and definitely had a unique flavor. Just make sure you have a few extra napkins handy, because the beignets are quite messy to eat. Overall, the prices for brunch are very reasonable ($10-13 per entree) and the waitstaff is terrifyingly efficient. I think the thought is to try to churn out dishes very quickly to accommodate as many customers as possible. However, we never felt rushed during our meal, and it was a great time. Lines were still long even after we left, so that definitely speaks to the popularity of the place. Anyways, Brenda's came with a great deal of hype, and despite the hype, the experience met my expectations and then some, and I'll definitely be back again.

I was visiting San Francisco for the weekend and wanted to try a good brunch! I was not disappointed. My hotel was in the union square area and I walked to Brenda's. It was about a 15 min walk. I passed through some interesting areas but it was daytime and no one bothered me. When I got to Brenda's (around 10:30am Saturday morning) it was packed! Wait was over a hour. Luckily, I was alone so I got seated immediately. I suggest if you come during peak brunch hours to come alone if you don't want to wait upwards of an hour plus. I ordered the shrimp and grits and some fries. I've never had grits before so wasn't sure what to expect but it was great. Very filling. The flavors blended together and the shrimp and tomatoes added to the dish. I hardly touched the fries cause the grits were enough. I definitely plan to visit Brenda's again and explore the menu more.

So we finally made it to Brenda's for a late lunch. Despite the scary looking line, it was actually not bad at all. We got our table in about 20-25 minutes. The host and wait staff are very helpful... We ordered Cajun Bloody-Mary's, Beignet Flight - pretty much a beignet sampler, Shrimp & Grits and Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict, side orders of bacon and Andouille Sausage. The grits were nice and creamy; however, I feel there was too much cheese and the overwhelmingly sweet tomato compote did not enhance the dish. In fact, it was more on the lines of a clash between flavors. The Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict was a little flat and had a single note. The seasoning did not "wow" us and the biscuits became quite soggy. Finally, the Beignet Sampler plate was decent. We found the beignets to be too heavy on the dough. (Yes, the crawfish beignet can justify for a thicker dough. But the dessert pastries should be light and airy.) So were we disappointed with the rave reviews? Yes, indeed!

    One of the better brunches I've experienced in recent memory. I was told to come early, so my friends and I arrived at 9:30am, and there was already a pretty long line. However, since we were a party of 3, we were seated after only about 20 minutes. We  had to get rid of our Philz coffee, because they don't allow outside coffee, which I felt was a little ridiculous. However, they did allow Libby Jane coffee, since it's a sister establishment of Brenda's.

    Anyways, we sat and got more coffee, ordered the beignet flight and our entrees. I predictably went with the crispy pork belly special, which came with cheesy grits, onion relish, and a poached egg. The pork belly slab was pretty sizable, and the grits were super rich, albeit a bit on the soupier side. But the dish came together very well, and I'm glad I ordered it.

    The sweet beignets were all delicious (plain, chocolate, and apple), and even the crawfish beignet was pretty good, and definitely had a unique flavor. Just make sure you have a few extra napkins handy, because the beignets are quite messy to eat.

    Overall, the prices for brunch are very reasonable ($10-13 per entree) and the waitstaff is terrifyingly efficient. I think the thought is to try to churn out dishes very quickly to accommodate as many customers as possible. However, we never felt rushed during our meal, and it was a great time. Lines were still long even after we left, so that definitely speaks to the popularity of the place. Anyways, Brenda's came with a great deal of hype, and despite the hype, the experience met my expectations and then some, and I'll definitely be back again.

    So we finally made it to Brenda's for a late lunch.  Despite the scary looking line, it was actually not bad at all.  We got our table in about 20-25 minutes.  The host and wait staff are very helpful...

    We ordered Cajun Bloody-Mary's, Beignet Flight - pretty much a beignet sampler, Shrimp & Grits and Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict, side orders of bacon and Andouille Sausage.

    The grits were nice and creamy; however, I feel there was too much cheese and the overwhelmingly sweet tomato compote did not enhance the dish.  In fact, it was more on the lines of a clash between flavors.

    The Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict was a little flat and had a single note.  The seasoning did not "wow" us and the biscuits became quite soggy.

    Finally, the Beignet Sampler plate was decent.  We found the beignets to be too heavy on the dough. (Yes, the crawfish beignet can justify for a thicker dough.  But the dessert pastries should be light and airy.)

    So were we disappointed with the rave reviews?  Yes, indeed!

    I really don't know why we waited 2 hours for this place? It wasn't anything too special imo. Being that it was our first time dining here, I had hoped that it would knock my socks off but it didn't.

    For the first hour and a half, we stood by a couple that were hugging pretty much the entire time. The chick must've thought that the crowd would sweep her bf away if she didn't hold on to him. Another chick in a party of 5 said excitedly, "I think we're next!" Only to wait another 30 min. AFTER we were seated. Yes, people watching can be fun when you're waiting this long.

    We ordered the beignet flight, fried chicken benedict, and the grillades and grits with coffee and watermelon sweet tea. The crawfish beignet was yummy as was the watermelon sweet tea. I couldn't really taste the fried chicken. I didn't have any of the other beignets or my home fries. Tried a little of the grillades and grits and it was ok. The couple seated next to us looked like they were totally unhappy. The one next to me made a lot of conversation to his sour puss faced bf (seated next to my hubby), but Mr. Sour puss himself barely said 2 words in response. Again, ppl watching is fun. They ordered something you could've ordered anywhere else, like Dennys.

    The price and wait for Brendas was really not worth it. Save yourselves the time and money and go elsewhere.
